{"title_page": "New Zealand Exhibition", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = \n| category        =\n| image           = The_New_Zealand_Industrial_Exhibition_Building_Dunedin_1865.jpg\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = New Zealand Exhibition Building, Dunedin, 1865\n| year            = 1865\n| name            = New Zealand Exhibition\n| motto           = \n| building        = \n| area            = \n| invent          = \n| visitors        = 31250\n| organized       = [[John Hyde Harris]], [[James Hector]], Alfred Eccles and [[Thomas Forrester (architect)|Thomas Forrester]]\n| cnt             = 12<!--NZ,Fiji,Australia,Canada,America,France,Belgium,Holland,Germany,Austria,GB,Indian court-->\n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = [[Colony of New Zealand]]\n| city            = [[Dunedin]]\n| venue           = \n| coord           = {{Coord|45|52|9.84|S|170|30|30.96|E}}\n| cand            = \n| award           = \n| open            = 12 January 1865\n| close           = 6 May 1865\n| prevexpo        = \n| prevcity        = \n| nextexpo        = \n| nextcity        = \n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = \n| prevsupcity     = \n| nextsuppl       = \n| nextsupcity     = \n| prevunho        = \n| prevunhocity    = \n| nextunho        = \n| nextunhocity    = \n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          =\n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''New Zealand Exhibition''' held in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand, in 1865 was a [[world's fair]]<ref name=\"FindPelp34\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Dunedin 1865\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=34\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | last= McCarthy\n | first = Conal\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169}}</ref> visited by 31250 people.<ref name=\"report\">{{cite web\n|first=Jock\n|last= Phillips\n|title=Exhibitions and world\u2019s fairs \u2013 New Zealand exhibitions, 1865 to 1900'\n|publisher=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/zoomify/45427/the-new-zealand-exhibition-dunedin-1865\n|accessdate= 31 August 2017\n}}</ref> \nIt was the first world's fair held in New Zealand.<ref name=\"FindPelp34\" /> \nIt opened on 12 January and ran until 6 May 1865.<ref name=\"figuresanddates\">{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/interactive/45443/attendance-at-major-new-zealand-exhibitions-1865-1940|accessdate=30 August 2017|title=Attendance at major New Zealand exhibitions, 1865\u20131940 \u2013 Exhibitions and world\u2019s fairs \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==Organisation==\nFollowing the Bazaar and Industrial Exhibition of 1862, held in Dunedin, a group of gentlemen formed a committee for the promotion of a similar exhibition to be held on a larger scale in Dunedin in 1865.  An application was made in February 1863 to the Governor requesting the formation of a Royal Commission, which was granted in May.  The Provincial Government provided the sum of \u00a34,000 for the aid of general purposes and another \u00a34,000 to build a suitable building.[[John Hyde Harris]] was president of the executive, [[James Hector]] was commissioner and [[Juried (competition)|juror]], Alfred Eccles the secretary<ref name=\"FindPelp418\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Appendix C:Fair Officials\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=418\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169\n | accessdate = }}</ref> and [[Thomas Forrester (architect)|Thomas Forrester]] building superintendent.<ref name=\"TFarch\">{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2f15/forrester-thomas|title=Forrester, Thomas \u2013 Biography \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n\nA low-level site on King Street was secured and a contract was let to Messrs. George Cornwell and Edward Horsman on November 11, 1863 for \u00a310,250 to erect the Main Building.  There was a large two-story stone Italianate building with clock tower and a series of annexes all designed by [[William Mason (architect)|Mason]] and [[William Clayton (architect)|Clayton]],<ref name=\"FindPelp35\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Dunedin 1865\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=35\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | last= McCarthy\n | first = Conal\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169\n | accessdate = }}</ref> \nwith a central courtyard derived from [[Charles Fowler|Fowler]]'s design of [[Covent Garden#Covent Garden market|Covent Garden market]].<ref name=\"cov\">{{cite web|url=http://archiseek.com/2012/1865-exhibition-building-dunedin-otago-new-zealand/|accessdate=30 August 2017|title=1865 \u2013 Exhibition Building, Dunedin, Otago, New Zealand \u2013 Architecture of New Zealand \u2013 Archiseek \u2013 Irish Architecture}}</ref>\nIt was not completely finished when the fair opened.<ref name=\"FindPelp35\" />\n\n==International Participation==\nFrom the America came exhibits from Canada and the United States. From Europe came exhibits from Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Great Britain, and the Netherlands. The sole Asian exhibiting nation was that of India.  From Oceania, the colonies of New Zealand were well represented as were New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, and Victoria.  Altogether there came 1,598 exhibits from about 700 exhibitors.\n\n==Legacy==\nExhibits from the exhibition provided the opening collection of the colonial museum, and added to the collection at the [[Otago Museum]],<ref name=\"FindPelp35\" /> and the main building was converted into a new hospital for Dunedin.  The old annex at the rear of the building was torn down in the mid-1890's, and a fire in the tower in 1897 almost destroyed the entire building.  The old exhibition hospital finally was torn down in 1933.<ref name=\"cov\" />\n\nAfter the exhibition, the collections were put into store and the art works were included in formation of [[Otago Society of Arts]] in 1876.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rice|first=Rebecca|date=2013|title=Creating culture in a colonial context:fine art at 1865 New Zealand Exhibition.|url=|journal=Anti-po-des Design Journal|volume=2|pages=11-23|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mp.natlib.govt.nz/detail/?id=3796&l=en Image of the exhibition building]\n*[http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Stout23-t6.html Official Catalogue of the New Zealand Exhibition 1865]\n*[http://www.enzb.auckland.ac.nz/document/?wid=4804 Jurors reports from the New Zealand Exhibition 1865]\n\n{{List of world fairs in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:1860s disestablishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Oceania]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Dunedin]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1860s in Dunedin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = \n| category        =\n| image           = The_New_Zealand_Industrial_Exhibition_Building_Dunedin_1865.jpg\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = New Zealand Exhibition Building, Dunedin, 1865\n| year            = 1865\n| name            = New Zealand Exhibition\n| motto           = \n| building        = \n| area            = \n| invent          = \n| visitors        = 31250\n| organized       = [[John Hyde Harris]], [[James Hector]], Alfred Eccles and [[Thomas Forrester (architect)|Thomas Forrester]]\n| cnt             = 12<!--NZ,Fiji,Australia,Canada,America,France,Belgium,Holland,Germany,Austria,GB,Indian court-->\n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = [[Colony of New Zealand]]\n| city            = [[Dunedin]]\n| venue           = \n| coord           = {{Coord|45|52|9.84|S|170|30|30.96|E}}\n| cand            = \n| award           = \n| open            = 12 January 1865\n| close           = 6 May 1865\n| prevexpo        = \n| prevcity        = \n| nextexpo        = \n| nextcity        = \n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = \n| prevsupcity     = \n| nextsuppl       = \n| nextsupcity     = \n| prevunho        = \n| prevunhocity    = \n| nextunho        = \n| nextunhocity    = \n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          =\n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''New Zealand Exhibition''' held in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand, in 1865 was a [[world's fair]]<ref name=\"FindPelp34\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Dunedin 1865\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=34\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | last= McCarthy\n | first = Conal\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169}}</ref> visited by 31250 people.<ref name=\"report\">{{cite web\n|first=Jock\n|last= Phillips\n|title=Exhibitions and world\u2019s fairs \u2013 New Zealand exhibitions, 1865 to 1900'\n|publisher=Te Ara \u2013 the Encyclopedia of New Zealand\n|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/zoomify/45427/the-new-zealand-exhibition-dunedin-1865\n|accessdate= 31 August 2017\n}}</ref> \nIt was the first world's fair held in New Zealand.<ref name=\"FindPelp34\" /> \nIt opened on 12 January and ran until 6 May 1865.<ref name=\"figuresanddates\">{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/interactive/45443/attendance-at-major-new-zealand-exhibitions-1865-1940|accessdate=30 August 2017|title=Attendance at major New Zealand exhibitions, 1865\u20131940 \u2013 Exhibitions and world\u2019s fairs \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==Organisation==\nFollowing the Bazaar and Industrial Exhibition of 1862, held in Dunedin, a group of gentlemen formed a committee for the promotion of a similar exhibition to be held on a larger scale in Dunedin in 1865.  An application was made in February 1863 to the Governor requesting the formation of a Royal Commission, which was granted in May.  The Provincial Government provided the sum of \u00a34,000 for the aid of general purposes and another \u00a34,000 to build a suitable building.[[John Hyde Harris]] was president of the executive, [[James Hector]] was commissioner and [[Juried (competition)|juror]], Alfred Eccles the secretary<ref name=\"FindPelp418\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Appendix C:Fair Officials\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=418\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169\n | accessdate = }}</ref> and [[Thomas Forrester (architect)|Thomas Forrester]] building superintendent.<ref name=\"TFarch\">{{cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2f15/forrester-thomas|title=Forrester, Thomas \u2013 Biography \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n\nA low-level site on King Street was secured and a contract was let to Messrs. George Cornwell and Edward Horsman on November 11, 1863 for \u00a310,250 to erect the Main Building.  There was a large two-story stone Italianate building with clock tower and a series of annexes all designed by [[William Mason (architect)|Mason]] and [[William Clayton (architect)|Clayton]],<ref name=\"FindPelp35\">{{cite encyclopedia\n | title = Dunedin 1865\n | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions\n | page=35\n | editor-last = Pelle\n | editor-first = Findling\n | last= McCarthy\n | first = Conal\n | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc\n | year = 2008\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780786434169\n | accessdate = }}</ref> \nwith a central courtyard derived from [[Charles Fowler|Fowler]]'s design of [[Covent Garden#Covent Garden market|Covent Garden market]].<ref name=\"cov\">{{cite web|url=http://archiseek.com/2012/1865-exhibition-building-dunedin-otago-new-zealand/|accessdate=30 August 2017|title=1865 \u2013 Exhibition Building, Dunedin, Otago, New Zealand \u2013 Architecture of New Zealand \u2013 Archiseek \u2013 Irish Architecture}}</ref>\nIt was not completely finished when the fair opened.<ref name=\"FindPelp35\" />\n\n==International Participation==\nFrom the America came exhibits from Canada and the United States. From Europe came exhibits from Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Great Britain, and the Netherlands. The sole Asian exhibiting nation was that of India.  From Oceania, the colonies of New Zealand were well represented as were New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, and Victoria.  Altogether there came 1,598 exhibits from about 700 exhibitors.\n\n==Legacy==\nExhibits from the exhibition provided the opening collection of the colonial museum, and added to the collection at the [[Otago Museum]],<ref name=\"FindPelp35\" /> and the main building became Dunedin's hospital until 1933.<ref name=\"cov\" />\n\nAfter the exhibition, the collections were put into store and the art works were included in formation of [[Otago Society of Arts]] in 1876.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rice|first=Rebecca|date=2013|title=Creating culture in a colonial context:fine art at 1865 New Zealand Exhibition.|url=|journal=Anti-po-des Design Journal|volume=2|pages=11-23|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mp.natlib.govt.nz/detail/?id=3796&l=en Image of the exhibition building]\n*[http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Stout23-t6.html Official Catalogue of the New Zealand Exhibition 1865]\n*[http://www.enzb.auckland.ac.nz/document/?wid=4804 Jurors reports from the New Zealand Exhibition 1865]\n\n{{List of world fairs in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:1860s disestablishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1865 disestablishments in Oceania]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Dunedin]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1860s in Dunedin]]\n", "name_user": "Mikeinlv", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Zealand_Exhibition"}
{"title_page": "Calhoun County, Mississippi", "text_new": "{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county  = Calhoun County\n| state = Mississippi\n| seal =\n| founded = 1852\n| seat wl= Pittsboro\n| largest city wl = Bruce\n| city type = town\n| area_total_sq_mi = 588\n| area_land_sq_mi = 587\n| area_water_sq_mi = 1.4\n| area percentage = 0.2\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 14962\n| pop_est_as_of = 2018\n| population_est = 14436\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| ex image           = Calhoun_County_Mississippi_Courthouse_January_2016.jpg\n| ex image size      =\n| ex image cap       = East fa\u00e7ade of Calhoun County Courthouse\n| web = http://calhouncoms.com/\n| district = 1st\n| time zone = Central\n| named for = [[John C. Calhoun]]\n}}\n\n'''Calhoun County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Mississippi]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 14,962.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/28/28013.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 3, 2013}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Pittsboro, Mississippi|Pittsboro]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref> The county is named after [[John C. Calhoun]], the [[U.S. Vice President]] and [[U.S. Senator]] from [[South Carolina]].\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|588|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|587|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|1.4|sqmi}} (0.2%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_28.txt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928074019/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_28.txt |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 28, 2013 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=November 3, 2014 |date=August 22, 2012 |title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files }}</ref>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Lafayette County, Mississippi|Lafayette County]] (north)\n* [[Pontotoc County, Mississippi|Pontotoc County]] (northeast)\n* [[Chickasaw County, Mississippi|Chickasaw County]] (east)\n* [[Webster County, Mississippi|Webster County]] (south)\n* [[Grenada County, Mississippi|Grenada County]] (southwest)\n* [[Yalobusha County, Mississippi|Yalobusha County]] (west)\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Major highways===\n* [[Image:Circle sign 8.svg|20px]] [[Mississippi Highway 8]]\n* [[Image:Circle sign 9.svg|20px]] [[Mississippi Highway 9]]\n* [[Image:Circle sign 32.svg|20px]] [[Mississippi Highway 32]]\n[[Mississippi Highway 9W]]\n\n===Airport===\nThe [[Calhoun County Airport (Mississippi)|Calhoun County Airport]] is a county-owned public-use [[airport]] located one nautical mile (1.2&nbsp;mi, 1.9&nbsp;km) southwest of the [[central business district]] of [[Pittsboro, Mississippi]].<ref>{{FAA-airport|ID=04M|use=PU|own=PU|site=11395.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. Effective 30 June 2011.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 9518\n|1870= 10561\n|1880= 13492\n|1900= 16512\n|1910= 17726\n|1920= 16823\n|1930= 18080\n|1940= 20893\n|1950= 18369\n|1960= 15941\n|1970= 14623\n|1980= 15664\n|1990= 14908\n|2000= 15069\n|2010= 14962\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=14436\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=November 3, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/ms190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder }}</ref> of 2000, there were 15,069 people, 6,019 households, and 4,255 families residing in the county.  The [[population density]] was 26 people per square mile (10/km\u00b2).  There were 6,902 housing units at an average density of 12 per square&nbsp;mile (5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the county was 69.41% [[Race (United States Census)|White or Caucasian]], 28.65% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.13% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.06% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.11% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.59% from two or more races.  2.11% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nAccording to the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, the largest ancestry groups in Calhoun County were [[English American|English]] 64.4%, [[African American|African]] 29% and [[Scots-Irish American|Scots-Irish]] 4.5%\n\nThere were 6,019 households out of which 31.60% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.00% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.40% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.30% were non-families. 27.10% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.90% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.46 and the average family size was 2.97.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 25.20% under the age of 18, 8.40% from 18 to 24, 27.00% from 25 to 44, 22.70% from 45 to 64, and 16.70% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females there were 90.70 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 87.00 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $27,113, and the median income for a family was $34,407. Males had a median income of $26,458 versus $19,491 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $15,106.  About 14.90% of families and 18.10% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 24.20% of those under age 18 and 21.80% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\nIn addition to the public high schools of Bruce, Calhoun City, and Vardaman, [[Calhoun Academy (Mississippi)|Calhoun Academy]] is a small K-12 private school which was founded as a [[segregation academy]], located between Pittsboro and Calhoun City.  This private school serves Calhoun and the surrounding counties. Calhoun academy's sports mascot is the cougar; Bruce's mascot is a Trojan; Calhoun City's mascot is a wildcat; and Vardaman's mascot is a ram.<ref>{{cite web | title = About | publisher = Calhoun Academy | url = http://www.calhounacademycougars.org/about | accessdate = December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n\n===Towns===\n* [[Bruce, Mississippi|Bruce]]\n* [[Calhoun City, Mississippi|Calhoun City]]\n* [[Derma, Mississippi|Derma]]\n* [[Vardaman, Mississippi|Vardaman]]\n\n===Villages===\n* [[Big Creek, Mississippi|Big Creek]]\n* [[Pittsboro, Mississippi|Pittsboro]] (county seat)\n* [[Slate Springs, Mississippi|Slate Springs]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Baileyville, Mississippi|Baileyville]]\n* [[Banner, Mississippi|Banner]]\n* [[Bently, Mississippi|Bently]]\n* [[Blueberry/Tater Bed Hill, Mississippi|Blueberry/Tater Bed Hill]]\n* [[Bull Mountain, Mississippi|Bull Mountain]]\n* [[Chickenbone, Mississippi|Chickenbone]]\n* [[Cottage Lane, Mississippi|Cottage Lane]]\n* [[Dentontown, Mississippi|Dentontown]]\n* [[Ellard, Mississippi|Ellard]]\n* [[Elzey, Mississippi|Elzey]]\n* [[Hollis Switch, Mississippi|Hollis Switch]]\n* [[Loyd, Mississippi|Loyd]]\n* [[Macedonia, Mississippi|Macedonia]]\n* [[New Gualley, Mississippi|New Gaulley]]\n* [[New Liberty, Mississippi|New Liberty]]\n* [[Old Town, Mississippi|Old Town]]\n* [[Reid, Mississippi|Reid]]\n* [[Sabougla, Mississippi|Sabougla]]\n* [[Sarepta, Mississippi|Sarepta]]\n* [[Spring Hill, Mississippi|Spring Hill]]\n* [[Wardwell, Mississippi|Wardwell]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Politics==\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Thir