{"title_page": "Typhoon Orchid (1991)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Typhoon Orchid (Sendang)\n| Type=typhoon\n| Year=1991\n| Basin=WPac\n| Image location=Orchid 1991 Oct 7 0521Z.jpg\n| Image name=Typhoon Orchid early on October 7\n| Formed={{start date|October 3, 1991}}\n| Dissipated={{end date|October 14, 1991}}\n| 1-min winds=115\n| 10-min winds=95\n| Pressure=930\n| Damages=15.8\n| Fatalities=1 direct, 2 indirect\n| Areas=[[Guam]], [[Japan]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1991 Pacific typhoon season]]\n}}\n'''Typhoon Orchid''', known in the Philippines as '''Typhoon Sendang''', was a long-lived [[typhoon]] that brushed [[Japan]] during October&nbsp;1991. An area of disturbed weather formed near the Caroline Islands in early October. A [[extratropical cyclone|mid-latitude cyclone]] weakened a [[subtropical ridge]] to its north, allowing the disturbance to slowly gain latitude, and on October&nbsp;3, the system organized into a tropical depression. On the next day, the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Orchid. Continuing to intensify, the cyclone strengthened into a typhoon on the morning of October&nbsp;6. Typhoon Orchid tracked due westward south of subtropical ridge while rapidly intensifying, and on October&nbsp;7, Orchid reached its peak intensity. Shortly after its peak, the typhoon began to recurve north as the ridge receded. After interacting with [[1991 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Pat|Typhoon Pat]], Orchid weakened below typhoon intensity on October&nbsp;12. After accelerating to the northwest while gradually weakening, Orchid transitioned into an extratropical cyclone on October&nbsp;14.\n\nIn conjunction with Pat, high waves claimed two lives on [[Guam]]. Because of the storm's slow movement as it tracked south of Japan, Typhoon Orchid dropped heavy precipitation across most of Japan. One person was killed and twenty people were injured across Japan. A total of 17&nbsp;flights were cancelled while 1,072&nbsp;trains were halted, stranding 342,000&nbsp;passengers. In addition, 18&nbsp;ferries were cancelled. The storm inflicted 249&nbsp;landslides, flooded over 675&nbsp;homes, and was accountable for extensive road damage in Japan. In all, damage was estimated at [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]2.15&nbsp;billion ([[United States Dollar|US]]$15.8 million).{{#tag:ref|All currencies are converted from Japanese yen to United States Dollars using [https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1991&year_result=1991&countryE%5B%5D=Japan this] with an exchange rate of the year 1991.|group=nb}}{{#tag:ref|All damage totals are in 1991 values of their respective currencies.|group=\"nb\"}}\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|Orchid 1991 track.png}}\nThe first tropical cyclone to develop during October&nbsp;1991, Typhoon Orchid formed a broad [[monsoon trough]] that extended from the South China Sea eastward through the Caroline Islands. The [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) started monitoring the system at 06:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;1 while it was located northwest of [[Guam]]. A [[trough (meteorology)|mid-latitude trough]] weakened a [[subtropical ridge]] to its north, allowing the tropical disturbance to slowly gain latitude. Following a surge in the monsoon trough, a [[Tropical Cyclone Formation Alert]] was issued at 08:00&nbsp;[[UTC]] on October&nbsp;3.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\">{{cite report|title=Annual Tropical Cyclone Report: 1991|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/atcr/1991atcr.pdf|author2=Naval Pacific Meteorology and Oceanography Center|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|accessdate=August 3, 2017|year=1992|format=[[PDF]]}}</ref> At the same time, the [[Japan Meteorological Agency]] (JMA) classified the system as a tropical depression,<ref name=\"JMA\">{{cite report|author=Japan Meteorological Agency|date=October 10, 1992|title=RSMC Best Track Data \u2013 1990\u20131999|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.jma.go.jp/jma/jma-eng/jma-center/rsmc-hp-pub-eg/Besttracks/bst9099.txt|format=[[.TXT]]}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [[Japan Meteorological Agency]] is the official [[Regional Specialized Meteorological Center]] for the western Pacific Ocean.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Japan Meteorological Agency|title=Annual Report on Activities of the RSMC Tokyo \u2013 Typhoon Center 2000|date=February 2001|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.jma.go.jp/jma/jma-eng/jma-center/rsmc-hp-pub-eg/AnnualReport/2000/Text/Text2000.pdf|page=3|format=PDF}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} with the JTWC doing the same at 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;4.{{#tag:ref|Wind estimates from the JMA and most other basins throughout the world are [[maximum sustained winds|sustained]] over 10&nbsp;minutes, while estimates from the United States-based Joint Typhoon Warning Center are sustained over 1&nbsp;minute. 10&#8209;minute winds are about 1.14 times the amount of 1&#8209;minute winds.<ref name=\"FAQD4\">{{cite book|author=Christopher W Landsea|author2=Hurricane Research Division|title=Frequently Asked Questions:|chapter=Subject: D4) What does \"maximum sustained wind\" mean? How does it relate to gusts in tropical cyclones?|accessdate=August 3, 2017|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/E7.html|date=April 26, 2004}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} Post-storm analysis from the JTWC indicated, however, that the depression had attained tropical storm midday on October&nbsp;3.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> The JMA upgraded Orchid into a tropical storm early on October&nbsp;4, and twenty-four hours later, the JMA upgraded Orchid into a [[tropical cyclone scales#West Pacific|severe tropical storm]].<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" /> At around this time, the [[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration]] (PAGASA) also monitored the storm and [[List of historical tropical cyclone names|assigned it with the local name]] ''Sendang''.<ref name=\"Old PAGASA Names\">{{cite report|url=http://www.typhoon2000.ph/oldPAGASAnames.jpg|title=Old PAGASA Names: List of names for tropical cyclones occurring within the Philippine Area of Responsibility 1991\u20132000|work=Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration|accessdate=August 3, 2017|publisher=Typhoon 2000}}</ref> On the evening of October&nbsp;5, Orchid was upgraded into a typhoon by the JTWC, and on the following morning, the JMA followed suit.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" />\n\nContinuing to intensify, Typhoon Orchid tracked due westward south of subtropical ridge.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> Late on October&nbsp;6, the JTWC raised the intensity of the storm to {{convert|115|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}, equal to a Category&nbsp;3 hurricane on the United States-based [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale]] (SSHWS).<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite report|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/best_tracks/1991/1991s-bwp/bwp231991.txt|title=Typhoon 23W Best Track|date=December 17, 2002|publisher=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|accessdate=August 3, 2017|format=TXT}}</ref> Increased convergence in the southern quadrant enhanced convection, and dual [[outflow (meteorology)|outflow channels]] aloft were present.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> The next day, the JTWC and JMA estimated that Orchid attained its peak intensity of {{convert|130|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> and {{convert|110|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"JMA\" /> Shortly after its peak, Orchid began to recurve near [[130th meridian east|130\u00b0E]] as the ridge receded eastward, allowing Orchid to move north. Typhoon Orchid slowly accelerated after recurvature, only to slow down south of Japan on October&nbsp;10 as a [[Fujiwhara effect|binary interaction]] started with [[Typhoon Pat (1991)|Typhoon Pat]]. Over a 42-hour period from October 10\u201312, Orchid took a \"stair-stepped\u201d track - moving to the north then back to the northeast due to interaction with Typhoon Pat.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> At 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;12, both the JTWC and JMA agreed that Pat lost typhoon intensity.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" /> Orchid subsequently started speeding up, following Pat to the northwest while slowly weakening. At 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;13, the final warning was issued by the JTWC since Orchid had transitioned into an [[extratropical cyclone]],<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> though according to the JMA, this process did not occur until 24 hours later.<ref name=\"JMA\" /> The JMA stopped keeping an eye on the system late on October&nbsp;15.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\">{{cite report|author1=Kenneth R. Knapp |author2=Michael C. Kruk |author3=David H. Levinson |author4=Howard J. Diamond |author5=Charles J. Neumann |year=2010|work=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS): Unifying tropical cyclone best track data|title=1991 ORCHID (1991274N14149)|publisher=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_current/browse-ibtracs/index.php?name=v03r09-1991274N14149}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough Typhoon Orchid spent much of its life over the open ocean, away from land, high surf, in conjunction with Pat, killed two people on Guam on October&nbsp;17. In addition, its slow movement south of Japan resulted in prolonged rains to much of the island nation.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /><ref name=\"DT\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=Typhoon 19921 (Orchid) |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/dsummary.pl?id=199121&basin=wnp&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=[[National Institute of Informatics]]|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak rainfall total of {{convert|762|mm|in|abbr=on}} occurred near [[Tokyo]].<ref name=\"DT2\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS HACHIJOJIMA (44261) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=44261&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak daily rainfall total of {{convert|307|mm|in|abbr=on}} was recorded at [[Ogatsu, Miyagi|Ogatsu]].<ref name=\"DT3\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS OGATSU (34241) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=34241&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak hourly rainfall total of {{convert|37|mm|in|abbr=on}} was observed in [[\u014cfunato, Iwate|\u014cfunato]].<ref name=\"DT4\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS OFUNATO (33877) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=33877&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A wind gust of {{convert|83|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} was recorded in Tokyo.<ref name=\"DT5\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS MIYAKEJIMA (44226) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=44226&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the southern portion of the island nation, 160&nbsp;households lost power in [[Okinawa Prefecture]]. Damage there amounted to \u00a556.4&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT6\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-936-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-936-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Offshore [[Honshu]], rough seas sunk the vessel ''Panama flag'' , although everyone there was rescued safely and only one person was wounded.<ref name=\"DT7\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-817-17 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-817-17&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Fifty-nine roads were damaged in [[Nara Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT8\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-780-18 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-780-18&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Forty-one trains were cancelled in [[Shiga Prefecture]], stranding 10,000&nbsp;passengers.<ref name=\"DT9\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-761-03 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-761-03&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Two homes were damaged in [[Yokohama]] due to heavy rains.<ref name=\"DT10\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-670-06 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-670-06&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In [[Hachij\u014d-jima]] and [[Aogashima]], there were a total of four landslides while in [[Izu \u014cshima|\u014cshima]] and [[Nii-jima]], five landslides were reported.<ref name=\"DT11\" /> [[Shin-Kodaira Station]] was submerged underwater due to landslides, flooding  {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} of train tracks. Officials estimated it would take several months to repair the damage. Nearby, tracks were lifted {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} due to pressure from underground water.<ref name=\"JEN2\" /> Six people were injured throughout [[Tokyo]], where the storm resulted in \u00a5240&nbsp;million in damage.<ref name=\"DT11\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-662-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-662-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In both [[Owase, Mie|Owase]] and [[Ayama District, Mie|Ayama]], one landslide occurred. Meanwhile, two landslides were reported in [[Nabari, Mie|Nabari]].<ref name=\"DT12\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-651-14 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-651-14&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Roads were damaged in 295 places and embankments were damaged in 98&nbsp;spots in [[Chiba Prefecture]]. A total of 995&nbsp;homes were damaged, and 69&nbsp;others were destroyed.<ref name=\"DT13\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-648-20 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-648-20&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Six people were injured there.<ref name=\"TTT\" /> Heavy rains damaged six homes and destroyed seven others in [[Yamanashi Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT14\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-638-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-638-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A total of 506&nbsp;houses were damaged and 31&nbsp;others were destroyed in [[Ibaraki Prefecture]]. Roads there were damaged in forty-one places, forcing five roads to close.<ref name=\"DT15\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-629-13 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-629-13&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Moisture from the storm, aided by a [[cold front]], damaged 275&nbsp;homes and destroyed 8&nbsp;other houses in [[Saitama Prefecture]], which resulted in 35&nbsp;losing their homes. Over {{convert|300|ha|acre|abbr=on}} of farmland was damaged, totaling \u00a5645&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT16\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-626-10 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-626-10&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Eighty-six homes were damaged in [[Gunma prefecture]], including forty-four in [[\u014cta, Gunma|\u014cta]], while four others were destroyed.<ref name=\"DT17\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-624-15 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-624-15&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A landslide blocked a road near [[Katsuyama, Fukui|Katsuyama]].<ref name=\"DT18\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-616-08 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-616-08&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A 43-year-old woman was killed because of a landslide in [[Fukushima Prefecture]], where six people were hurt.<ref name=\"DT19\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-595-08 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-595-08&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Seventeen dwellings were damaged and destroyed in [[Yamagata Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT20\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-588-03 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-588-03&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Heavy rains deluged [[Iwate Prefecture]], damaging seventy-nine houses and destroying seven others. Roads suffered damage in 196&nbsp;places and damage totaled at \u00a5657&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT21\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-584-07 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-584-07&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Damage in [[Aomori Prefecture]] was estimated at \u00a5557&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT22\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-575-04 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-575-04&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOverall, one person was killed<ref name=\"TTT\">{{cite news|title=Tropical storm moves along Japan's coast|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12929999/ttt/|accessdate=August 7, 2017|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Town Talk|date=October 14, 1991}}{{subscription required|via=newspapers.com}</ref> and twenty people were injured across Japan.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> A total of 17&nbsp;flights were cancelled<ref name=\"JEN1\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Likely to hit Honshu|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 11, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> while 1,072&nbsp;trains were halted, which affected 342,000&nbsp;passengers.<ref name=\"JEN2\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Triggered Landslides, Kills One, Injuries Eight|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 12, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> Eighteen ferries were cancelled.<ref name=\"JEN3\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Paralyses transport in Eastern Japan|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 13, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> The storm produced 249&nbsp;landslides,<ref name=\"HKO\">{{cite report|author1=[[Hong Kong Observatory]]|title=Meteorological Results: 1991|chapter=Part III \u2013 Tropical Cyclone Summaries|journal=Meteorological Results|year=1992|url=http://www.hko.gov.hk/publica/tc/tc1991.pdf|accessdate=August 3, 2017|pages=16|publisher=Hong Kong Observatory|format=PDF}}</ref> flooded over 675&nbsp;homes, and was accountable for extensive road damage in Japan.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> Damage was estimated at \u00a52.15&nbsp;billion (US$15.8&nbsp;million).<ref name=\"DT6\" /><ref name=\"DT11\" /><ref name=\"DT16\" /><ref name=\"DT21\" /><ref name=\"DT22\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[Typhoon Page (1990)]] - similar late-season Japan-hitting typhoon\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{1991 Pacific typhoon season buttons}}\n\n[[Category:1991 Pacific typhoon season|O]]\n[[Category:Typhoons in Japan|O]]\n[[Category:1991 in Japan|O]]\n[[Category:Typhoons|O]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Typhoon Orchid (Sendang)\n| Type=typhoon\n| Year=1991\n| Basin=WPac\n| Image location=Orchid 1991 Oct 7 0521Z.jpg\n| Image name=Typhoon Orchid early on October 7\n| Formed={{start date|October 3, 1991}}\n| Dissipated={{end date|October 14, 1991}}\n| 1-min winds=115\n| 10-min winds=95\n| Pressure=930\n| Damages=15.8\n| Fatalities=1 direct, 2 indirect\n| Areas=[[Guam]], [[Japan]]\n| Hurricane season=[[1991 Pacific typhoon season]]\n}}\n'''Typhoon Orchid''', known in the Philippines as '''Typhoon Sendang''', was a long-lived [[typhoon]] that brushed [[Japan]] during October&nbsp;1991. An area of disturbed weather formed near the Caroline Islands in early October. A [[extratropical cyclone|mid-latitude cyclone]] weakened a [[subtropical ridge]] to its north, allowing the disturbance to slowly gain latitude, and on October&nbsp;3, the system organized into a tropical depression. On the next day, the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Orchid. Continuing to intensify, the cyclone strengthened into a typhoon on the morning of October&nbsp;6. Typhoon Orchid tracked due westward south of subtropical ridge while rapidly intensifying, and on October&nbsp;7, Orchid reached its peak intensity. Shortly after its peak, the typhoon began to recurve north as the ridge receded. After interacting with [[1991 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Pat|Typhoon Pat]], Orchid weakened below typhoon intensity on October&nbsp;12. After accelerating to the northwest while gradually weakening, Orchid transitioned into an extratropical cyclone on October&nbsp;14.\n\nIn conjunction with Pat, high waves claimed two lives on [[Guam]]. Because of the storm's slow movement as it tracked south of Japan, Typhoon Orchid dropped heavy precipitation across most of Japan. One person was killed and twenty people were injured across Japan. A total of 17&nbsp;flights were cancelled while 1,072&nbsp;trains were halted, stranding 342,000&nbsp;passengers. In addition, 18&nbsp;ferries were cancelled. The storm inflicted 249&nbsp;landslides, flooded over 675&nbsp;homes, and was accountable for extensive road damage in Japan. In all, damage was estimated at [[Japanese yen|\u00a5]]2.15&nbsp;billion ([[United States Dollar|US]]$15.8 million).{{#tag:ref|All currencies are converted from Japanese yen to United States Dollars using [https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=1991&year_result=1991&countryE%5B%5D=Japan this] with an exchange rate of the year 1991.|group=nb}}{{#tag:ref|All damage totals are in 1991 values of their respective currencies.|group=\"nb\"}}\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|Orchid 1991 track.png}}\nThe first tropical cyclone to develop during October&nbsp;1991, Typhoon Orchid formed a broad [[monsoon trough]] that extended from the South China Sea eastward through the Caroline Islands. The [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) started monitoring the system at 06:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;1 while it was located northwest of [[Guam]]. A [[trough (meteorology)|mid-latitude trough]] weakened a [[subtropical ridge]] to its north, allowing the tropical disturbance to slowly gain latitude. Following a surge in the monsoon trough, a [[Tropical Cyclone Formation Alert]] was issued at 08:00&nbsp;[[UTC]] on October&nbsp;3.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\">{{cite report|title=Annual Tropical Cyclone Report: 1991|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/atcr/1991atcr.pdf|author2=Naval Pacific Meteorology and Oceanography Center|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|accessdate=August 3, 2017|year=1992|format=[[PDF]]}}</ref> At the same time, the [[Japan Meteorological Agency]] (JMA) classified the system as a tropical depression,<ref name=\"JMA\">{{cite report|author=Japan Meteorological Agency|date=October 10, 1992|title=RSMC Best Track Data \u2013 1990\u20131999|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.jma.go.jp/jma/jma-eng/jma-center/rsmc-hp-pub-eg/Besttracks/bst9099.txt|format=[[.TXT]]}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [[Japan Meteorological Agency]] is the official [[Regional Specialized Meteorological Center]] for the western Pacific Ocean.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Japan Meteorological Agency|title=Annual Report on Activities of the RSMC Tokyo \u2013 Typhoon Center 2000|date=February 2001|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.jma.go.jp/jma/jma-eng/jma-center/rsmc-hp-pub-eg/AnnualReport/2000/Text/Text2000.pdf|page=3|format=PDF}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} with the JTWC doing the same at 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;4.{{#tag:ref|Wind estimates from the JMA and most other basins throughout the world are [[maximum sustained winds|sustained]] over 10&nbsp;minutes, while estimates from the United States-based Joint Typhoon Warning Center are sustained over 1&nbsp;minute. 10&#8209;minute winds are about 1.14 times the amount of 1&#8209;minute winds.<ref name=\"FAQD4\">{{cite book|author=Christopher W Landsea|author2=Hurricane Research Division|title=Frequently Asked Questions:|chapter=Subject: D4) What does \"maximum sustained wind\" mean? How does it relate to gusts in tropical cyclones?|accessdate=August 3, 2017|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/E7.html|date=April 26, 2004}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}} Post-storm analysis from the JTWC indicated, however, that the depression had attained tropical storm midday on October&nbsp;3.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> The JMA upgraded Orchid into a tropical storm early on October&nbsp;4, and twenty-four hours later, the JMA upgraded Orchid into a [[tropical cyclone scales#West Pacific|severe tropical storm]].<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" /> At around this time, the [[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration]] (PAGASA) also monitored the storm and [[List of historical tropical cyclone names|assigned it with the local name]] ''Sendang''.<ref name=\"Old PAGASA Names\">{{cite report|url=http://www.typhoon2000.ph/oldPAGASAnames.jpg|title=Old PAGASA Names: List of names for tropical cyclones occurring within the Philippine Area of Responsibility 1991\u20132000|work=Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration|accessdate=August 3, 2017|publisher=Typhoon 2000}}</ref> On the evening of October&nbsp;5, Orchid was upgraded into a typhoon by the JTWC, and on the following morning, the JMA followed suit.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" />\n\nContinuing to intensify, Typhoon Orchid tracked due westward south of subtropical ridge.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> Late on October&nbsp;6, the JTWC raised the intensity of the storm to {{convert|115|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}, equal to a Category&nbsp;3 hurricane on the United States-based [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale]] (SSHWS).<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite report|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/best_tracks/1991/1991s-bwp/bwp231991.txt|title=Typhoon 23W Best Track|date=December 17, 2002|publisher=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|accessdate=August 3, 2017|format=TXT}}</ref> Increased convergence in the southern quadrant enhanced convection, and dual [[outflow (meteorology)|outflow channels]] aloft were present.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> The next day, the JTWC and JMA estimated that Orchid attained its peak intensity of {{convert|130|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> and {{convert|110|mph|km/h|abbr=on|round=5|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"JMA\" /> Shortly after its peak, Orchid began to recurve near [[130th meridian east|130\u00b0E]] as the ridge receded eastward, allowing Orchid to move north. Typhoon Orchid slowly accelerated after recurvature, only to slow down south of Japan on October&nbsp;10 as a [[Fujiwhara effect|binary interaction]] started with [[Typhoon Pat (1991)|Typhoon Pat]]. Over a 42-hour period from October 10-12, Orchid took a \"stair-stepped\u201d track - moving to the north then back to the northeast due to interaction with Typhoon Pat.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> At 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;12, both the JTWC and JMA agreed that Pat lost typhoon intensity.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\" /> Orchid subsequently started speeding up, following Pat to the northwest while slowly weakening. At 00:00&nbsp;UTC on October&nbsp;13, the final warning was issued by the JTWC since Orchid had transitioned into an [[extratropical cyclone]],<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> though according to the JMA, this process did not occur until 24 hours later.<ref name=\"JMA\" /> The JMA stopped keeping an eye on the system late on October&nbsp;15.<ref name=\"IBTRACS\">{{cite report|author1=Kenneth R. Knapp |author2=Michael C. Kruk |author3=David H. Levinson |author4=Howard J. Diamond |author5=Charles J. Neumann |year=2010|work=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS): Unifying tropical cyclone best track data|title=1991 ORCHID (1991274N14149)|publisher=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|accessdate=August 3, 2017|url=http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_current/browse-ibtracs/index.php?name=v03r09-1991274N14149}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nAlthough Typhoon Orchid spent much of its life over the open ocean, away from land, high surf, in conjunction with Pat, killed two people on Guam on October&nbsp;17. In addition, its slow movement south of Japan resulted in prolonged rains to much of the island nation.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /><ref name=\"DT\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=Typhoon 19921 (Orchid) |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/dsummary.pl?id=199121&basin=wnp&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=[[National Institute of Informatics]]|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak rainfall total of {{convert|762|mm|in|abbr=on}} occurred near [[Tokyo]].<ref name=\"DT2\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS HACHIJOJIMA (44261) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=44261&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak daily rainfall total of {{convert|307|mm|in|abbr=on}} was recorded at [[Ogatsu, Miyagi|Ogatsu]].<ref name=\"DT3\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS OGATSU (34241) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=34241&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A peak hourly rainfall total of {{convert|37|mm|in|abbr=on}} was observed in [[\u014cfunato, Iwate|\u014cfunato]].<ref name=\"DT4\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS OFUNATO (33877) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=33877&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> A wind gust of {{convert|83|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} was recorded in Tokyo.<ref name=\"DT5\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|title=AMeDAS MIYAKEJIMA (44226) @ Typhoon 199121|url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/amedas/graph.pl?number=44226&id=199121&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the southern portion of the island nation, 160&nbsp;households lost power in [[Okinawa Prefecture]]. Damage there amounted to \u00a556.4&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT6\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-936-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-936-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Offshore [[Honshu]], rough seas sunk the vessel ''Panama flag'' , although everyone there was rescued safely and only one person was wounded.<ref name=\"DT7\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-817-17 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-817-17&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Fifty-nine roads were damaged in [[Nara Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT8\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-780-18 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-780-18&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Forty-one trains were cancelled in [[Shiga Prefecture]], stranding 10,000&nbsp;passengers.<ref name=\"DT9\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-761-03 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-761-03&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Two homes were damaged in [[Yokohama]] due to heavy rains.<ref name=\"DT10\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-670-06 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-670-06&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In [[Hachij\u014d-jima]] and [[Aogashima]], there were a total of four landslides while in [[Izu \u014cshima|\u014cshima]] and [[Nii-jima]], five landslides were reported.<ref name=\"DT11\" /> [[Shin-Kodaira Station]] was submerged underwater due to landslides, flooding  {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} of train tracks. Officials estimated it would take several months to repair the damage. Nearby, tracks were lifted {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} due to pressure from underground water.<ref name=\"JEN2\" /> Six people were injured throughout [[Tokyo]], where the storm resulted in \u00a5240&nbsp;million in damage.<ref name=\"DT11\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-662-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-662-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In both [[Owase, Mie|Owase]] and [[Ayama District, Mie|Ayama]], one landslide occurred. Meanwhile, two landslides were reported in [[Nabari, Mie|Nabari]].<ref name=\"DT12\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-651-14 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-651-14&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Roads were damaged in 295 places and embankments were damaged in 98&nbsp;spots in [[Chiba Prefecture]]. A total of 995&nbsp;homes were damaged, and 69&nbsp;others were destroyed.<ref name=\"DT13\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-648-20 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-648-20&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Six people were injured there.<ref name=\"TTT\" /> Heavy rains damaged six homes and destroyed seven others in [[Yamanashi Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT14\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-638-09 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-638-09&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A total of 506&nbsp;houses were damaged and 31&nbsp;others were destroyed in [[Ibaraki Prefecture]]. Roads there were damaged in forty-one places, forcing five roads to close.<ref name=\"DT15\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-629-13 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-629-13&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Moisture from the storm, aided by a [[cold front]], damaged 275&nbsp;homes and destroyed 8&nbsp;other houses in [[Saitama Prefecture]], which resulted in 35&nbsp;losing their homes. Over {{convert|300|ha|acre|abbr=on}} of farmland was damaged, totaling \u00a5645&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT16\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-626-10 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-626-10&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Eighty-six homes were damaged in [[Gunma prefecture]], including forty-four in [[\u014cta, Gunma|\u014cta]], while four others were destroyed.<ref name=\"DT17\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-624-15 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-624-15&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A landslide blocked a road near [[Katsuyama, Fukui|Katsuyama]].<ref name=\"DT18\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-616-08 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-616-08&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> A 43-year-old woman was killed because of a landslide in [[Fukushima Prefecture]], where six people were hurt.<ref name=\"DT19\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-595-08 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-595-08&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Seventeen dwellings were damaged and destroyed in [[Yamagata Prefecture]].<ref name=\"DT20\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-588-03 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-588-03&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Heavy rains deluged [[Iwate Prefecture]], damaging seventy-nine houses and destroying seven others. Roads suffered damage in 196&nbsp;places and damage totaled at \u00a5657&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT21\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-584-07 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-584-07&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Damage in [[Aomori Prefecture]] was estimated at \u00a5557&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DT22\">{{cite report|first1=Kitamoto|last1=Asanobu|language=Japanese|title=1991-575-04 |url=http://agora.ex.nii.ac.jp/cgi-bin/dt/report.pl?id=1991-575-04&lang=en|website=Digital Typhoon|publisher=National Institute of Informatics|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOverall, one person was killed<ref name=\"TTT\">{{cite news|title=Tropical storm moves along Japan's coast|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12929999/ttt/|accessdate=August 7, 2017|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Town Talk|date=October 14, 1991}}{{subscription required|via=newspapers.com}</ref> and twenty people were injured across Japan.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> A total of 17&nbsp;flights were cancelled<ref name=\"JEN1\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Likely to hit Honshu|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 11, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> while 1,072&nbsp;trains were halted, which affected 342,000&nbsp;passengers.<ref name=\"JEN2\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Triggered Landslides, Kills One, Injuries Eight|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 12, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> Eighteen ferries were cancelled.<ref name=\"JEN3\">{{cite news|title=Typhoon Paralyses transport in Eastern Japan|newspaper=Japanese Economic Newswire|date=October 13, 1991}} {{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> The storm produced 249&nbsp;landslides,<ref name=\"HKO\">{{cite report|author1=[[Hong Kong Observatory]]|title=Meteorological Results: 1991|chapter=Part III \u2013 Tropical Cyclone Summaries|journal=Meteorological Results|year=1992|url=http://www.hko.gov.hk/publica/tc/tc1991.pdf|accessdate=August 3, 2017|pages=16|publisher=Hong Kong Observatory|format=PDF}}</ref> flooded over 675&nbsp;homes, and was accountable for extensive road damage in Japan.<ref name=\"JTWC ATCR\" /> Damage was estimated at \u00a52.15&nbsp;billion (US$15.8&nbsp;million).<ref name=\"DT6\" /><ref name=\"DT11\" /><ref name=\"DT16\" /><ref name=\"DT21\" /><ref name=\"DT22\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[Typhoon Page (1990)]] - similar late-season Japan-hitting typhoon\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{1991 Pacific typhoon season buttons}}\n\n[[Category:1991 Pacific typhoon season|O]]\n[[Category:Typhoons in Japan|O]]\n[[Category:1991 in Japan|O]]\n[[Category:Typhoons|O]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMeteorological history:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 10-12 \u2192 10\u201312", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typhoon_Orchid_(1991)"}
